\begin_layout Section
Long-term Assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tangible assets maintain physical evidence of existence (PP&E, land).
 Only those that have a definite useful life are depreciated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intanbigle assets have no physical substance (patent, trademark, copyrights).
 They are depreciated only if they have a definite useful life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 3 components in an asset cost:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Purchase price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Indirect cost
\series default
 (bringing the asset to the location and condition to operate)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Improvements
\series default
 (extending the usefule life, increasing the output/quality)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any cost from the asset purchase to beginning its operation is 
\series bold
capitalized
\series default
.
 Afterwards, the asset is 
\series bold
depreciated
\series default
 throughout its useful life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to achive matching, the cost of an asset is allocated over the
 time it is used to produce revenue.
\end_layout

