\begin_layout Subsection
Straight-line method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the simplest method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the straight-line method, the cost is equally distributed over its useful
 life:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Depreciation\,expense=\frac{Asset\,cost-Residual\,value}{Useful\,life}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Double-declining-balance method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The depreciation starts fast and declines afterwards:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
DDB=2\times100\%/Life
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Depreciation\,expense=NBV\times DDB
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last year depreciation expense is calculated as a plug number (to ensure
 not depreciating below the salvage value).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unit-of-production method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this method the asset is depreciated according to the actual usage, calculate
d in produced units:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Depreciation\,Rate=\frac{Asset\,cost-Residual\,value}{Total\,units\,to\,be\,made}=Depreciation\,rate\,per\,unit
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Depreciation\,expense=Depreciation\,rate\,per\,unit\times units\,made
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

